SIMPLE: innovate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Innovate
<hw>In"no*vate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Innovated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Innovating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>innovatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>innovare</ets> to revew; pref.
<ets>in-</ets> in + <ets>novare</ets> to make new, fr. <ets>novus</ets>
new. See <er>New</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To bring in as new; to
introduce as a novelty; <as>as, to <ex>innovate</ex> a word or an
act</as>.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To change or alter by introducing something new; to
remodel; to revolutionize.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark>
<rj><au>Burton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From his attempts upon the civil power, he proceeds⟦br⟧
to <qex>innovate</qex> God's worship.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Innovate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Innovate
<hw>In"no*vate</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To introduce novelties or
changes; -- sometimes with <xex>in</xex> or <xex>on</xex>.</def>
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Every man, therefore, is not fit to <qex>innovate</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Innovation</ent>⟦br⟧
